Modern residential architecture in Poland is increasingly characterized by a blend of minimalist aesthetics, natural materials, and "modern barn" styles that feature simple, gabled forms with dark metal cladding. These homes often maximize their connection to the surrounding landscape through extensive floor-to-ceiling glazing while maintaining privacy with clever, sometimes L-shaped layouts. Interior spaces typically emphasize open-concept designs, raw materials like concrete or timber, and smart, functional layouts to fit specific site conditions, such as slopes or forests. Furthermore, many new Polish homes are designed with sustainability in mind, utilizing eco-friendly materials and energy-efficient, often passive, technologies.
